<div class="flex flex-col gap-5">
	<p>
		For Mark Dorf, environmental media is no longer about capturing pristine landscapes but about exposing how nature moves, appears, and circulates as ideology. In his two film installations <em>A New Nature</em> and <em>Homecoming</em>, scientific confidence meets its limits. Traditional cinematic media, social media fragments and AI animations reveal the digital mediation of every so-called "natural" encounter. The mountain constructed from scattered photographs becomes geographic fiction—beautiful enough to make decisions upon, yet utterly artificial.
	</p>
	<p>
		Dorf treats nature representation as both political act and survival strategy. His deliberate avoidance of scientific data visualization exposes default assumptions embedded in environmental media, while his shift toward embodying ecological processes reflects a recognition of "the importance of visibility" in research-dominated spaces. A recurring strategy in his practice is the deployment of fictional landscapes as resistance, drawing on systems thinking to expose representational violence. This strategic use of artifice functions as camouflage, transmitting complex messages about scientific authority and environmental fantasy through seemingly documentary forms.
	</p>
</div>
